onstrates that candidates can get a premium in support from the policy reputations of their parties. In particular, Paul Sniderman and Edward Stiglitz present a theory of how partisans take account of the parties' policy reputations as a function of the competing candidates' policy positions. A central implication of this theory of reputation-centered choices is that party identification gives candidates tremendous latitude in their policy positioning. Paradoxically, it is the party supporters who understand and are in synch with the ideological logic of the American party system who open the door to a polarized politics precisely by making the best-informed choices on offer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aParty affiliation. 0aPolitical partiesxPublic opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aAmerican party system.  aAmerican politics.  aDemocrats.  aRepublicans.  acandidate positioning.  ademocratic experiment.  ademocratic politics.  aelected representatives.  aelectoral punishment.  apartisans.  aparty identification.  apolicy conviction.  apolicy positions.  apolicy preferences.  apolicy reputations.  apolicy-based voting.  apolitical competence.  apolitical landscape.  apolitical parties.  apolitical party.  aprogrammatic partisanship.  aprogrammatic party identifiers.  areputational premium.  aspatial reasoning.  aspatial voting.  asupply-side theory.  avoters.1 aStiglitz, Edward H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400842551zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400842551423Coveruhttps://www